<p class="article-lead">EDP, EDT and extrait are useful positioning terms, but they do not guarantee one universal fragrance percentage or performance level. The formula, materials, carrier and market convention matter.</p><h2>Concentration is a formulation decision</h2><p>More concentrate can increase material cost and change diffusion, color, solubility and dry-down. It does not automatically make every composition perform better. Some formulas feel clearer at a lower dosage; others need reformulation when moved to extrait strength.</p><h2>Specify the product, not only the label</h2><p>Agree the intended dosage, carrier system, bottle size, spray delivery and claims. Evaluate samples at the proposed concentration and keep the approved formula reference. Destination-market label and safety review should use the actual composition rather than assumptions attached to “EDP” or “extrait.”</p>
